#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:1
msgid "How Guidelines Are Written"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:3
msgid ""
"The guidelines in this collection reflect a set of widely-recognized "
"**philosophy** and **principles** for writing high-quality software. Three "
"books have influenced the guidelines the most:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:7
msgid ""
"[_The Art of Readable Code_](https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/the-art-"
"of/9781449318482/)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:8
msgid ""
"[_Clean Code_](https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/clean-code-"
"a/9780136083238/)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:9
msgid "[_Code Complete_](https://stevemcconnell.com/books/)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:11
msgid ""
"The guidelines are derived from **code review experience**, where we point "
"out code smells, observe anti-patterns, and fix recurring bugs. By the time "
"the initial version of these guidelines was formulated, Asterinas had seen "
"thousands of code reviews. We collected the historical review comments as a "
"[dataset](https://github.com/asterinas/pr-review-analysis) and used it as "
"both inspiration and evidence."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:19
msgid ""
"The remainder of this page moves from values to practice. The [Philosophy]"
"(#philosophy) section captures foundational beliefs about what makes code "
"understandable and maintainable. The [Principles](#principles) section turns "
"those beliefs into design-level rules that guide everyday decisions. "
"Finally, the [Quality Criteria](#quality-criteria) section defines how "
"individual guidelines are written and accepted into this collection."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:28
msgid "Philosophy"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:30
msgid "Minimize time to understand"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:32
msgid ""
"Code should be written to minimize the time it would take someone else to "
"fully understand it. This is the fundamental theorem of readability and the "
"single most important measure of code quality in this project. \"Someone "
"else\" includes your future self."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:39
msgid ""
"Code is read far more often than it is written. If a technique makes code "
"shorter but harder to follow at a glance, choose clarity over brevity."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:44
msgid "Managing complexity is the primary technical imperative"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:46
msgid ""
"No one can hold an entire modern program in their head. The purpose of every "
"technique in software construction — decomposition, naming, encapsulation, "
"abstraction — is to break complex problems into simple pieces so that you "
"can safely focus on one thing at a time."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:52
msgid "Craftsmanship and care"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:54
msgid ""
"Clean code looks like it was written by someone who cares. Professionalism "
"means never knowingly leaving a mess. The only way to go fast is to keep the "
"code clean at all times."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:58
msgid "Continuous improvement"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:60
msgid ""
"Leave code cleaner than you found it. Small, steady improvements — renaming "
"a variable, extracting a function, eliminating duplication — prevent code "
"from rotting over time."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:66
msgid "Principles"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:68
msgid "Single Responsibility"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:70
msgid ""
"Each module, type, or function should have one, and only one, reason to "
"change. If you cannot describe what a unit does without the words \"and,\" "
"\"or,\" or \"but,\" it has too many responsibilities."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:76
msgid "Don't Repeat Yourself (DRY)"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:78
msgid ""
"Every piece of knowledge should have a single, unambiguous representation. "
"Duplication harms readability and maintainability. When the same pattern "
"appears three or more times, eliminate the duplication (e.g., adding a "
"helper function)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:84
msgid "Information Hiding"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:86
msgid ""
"Hide design decisions behind well-defined interfaces. A module's public "
"surface should contain only what its consumers need. Internal data "
"structures, helper types, and bookkeeping fields should remain private."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:92
msgid "Open for Extension, Closed for Modification"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:94
msgid ""
"Stable modules and APIs should be open to extension but closed to breaking "
"modification. Prefer adding new behavior through existing interfaces "
"(traits, enums, and pluggable components) instead of repeatedly editing "
"established call paths. Do not introduce extension points preemptively; add "
"them when there is a concrete extension need."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:104
msgid "Least Surprise"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:106
msgid ""
"Functions, types, and APIs should behave as their names and signatures "
"suggest. When an obvious behavior is not implemented, readers lose trust in "
"the codebase and must fall back on reading implementation details."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:112
msgid "Loose Coupling, Strong Cohesion"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:114
msgid ""
"Connections between modules should be small, visible, and flexible. Within a "
"module, every part should contribute to a single, well-defined purpose."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:119
msgid "Consistency"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:121
msgid ""
"Do similar things the same way throughout the codebase. Consistency reduces "
"surprise and cognitive load even when neither approach is objectively "
"superior. When a convention already exists, follow it; do not introduce a "
"competing convention without compelling justification."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:128
msgid "Test as the Source of Confidence"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:130
msgid ""
"Tests exist to make change safe. A comprehensive test suite should give "
"developers confidence that a passing run means the system works and a "
"failing run pinpoints what broke. Every test must earn its place by "
"increasing that confidence. A test that does not — flaky tests, tautological "
"assertions, tests coupled to implementation details — is worse than no test "
"at all."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:141
msgid "Rust-Native Approach"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:143
msgid ""
"Asterinas is inspired by Linux but is not a C port. The language shapes how "
"we think about problems: where C code relies on conventions and manual "
"discipline (return-code checking, paired init/cleanup, header-file "
"contracts), Rust offers compiler-enforced, zero-cost abstractions (the `?` "
"operator, RAII, trait bounds)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:150
msgid ""
"Learn from Linux's design, not its idioms. The result should read like "
"idiomatic Rust, not like C written in Rust syntax."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:154
msgid "Quality Criteria"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:156
msgid ""
"Every guideline carries a **descriptive short name** in kebab-case (e.g., "
"`explain-variables`, `lock-ordering`). Short names are kept **intact** even "
"as the guidelines evolve and should be used when referencing guidelines in "
"code reviews."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:161
msgid ""
"A guideline is accepted into this collection when it satisfies all four "
"quality criteria:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:164
msgid ""
"**Concrete** — Framed as an actionable item with an illustrating example "
"when possible."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:166
msgid "**Concise** — Kept short; we do not want to intimidate readers."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:168
msgid ""
"**Grounded** — Opinionated or non-obvious guidelines should include a \"See "
"also\" line with supportive materials (literature, PR reviews, codebase "
"examples)."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:171
msgid ""
"**Relevant** — Included only if it has codebase examples, prevents a past "
"bug, or matches anti-patterns observed in code reviews."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:176
msgid ""
"When present, the **\"See also\" line** lists sources in the order: "
"literature; PR reviews; codebase examples. Not every guideline needs all "
"three; for strongly opinionated or non-obvious guidelines, include the line "
"by default."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:182
msgid ""
"Do not add a guideline whose only value is mechanical enforcement already "
"provided by automated tools such as [rustfmt](https://github.com/rust-lang/"
"rustfmt) and [clippy](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust-clippy). If a tool-"
"enforced convention appears frequently in review or needs project-specific "
"rationale, keep a short explanatory guideline and point to the tool "
"configuration."
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:189
msgid "Example"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:191
msgid "Below is a sample guideline demonstrating these conventions:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:217
msgid "This example demonstrates:"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:218
msgid ""
"A stable short name (`explain-variables`) shown parenthetically and used as "
"the heading anchor"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:219
msgid "A one-sentence actionable recommendation followed by a code example"
msgstr ""

#: src/to-contribute/coding-guidelines/how-guidelines-are-written.md:220
msgid ""
"A \"See also\" line ordered as: literature, PR reviews, codebase examples"
msgstr ""
